bootaa64.efi and dejavu-mono.pf2, vendored from ROCKNIX's own compiled GRUB
for SM8250 handhelds.

Source: https://github.com/ROCKNIX/distribution release tag 20260701,
SM8250 update tar (ROCKNIX-SM8250.aarch64-20260701.tar), extracted from
3rdparty/bootloader/EFI/BOOT/bootaa64.efi and
3rdparty/bootloader/boot/grub/dejavu-mono.pf2.

Why: Fedora's own grub2-efi (shim -> grubaa64.efi) never reliably registered
button-press input on these devices' GRUB menu (reported broken on Flip2 and
RP5), and never correctly remembered the last-selected boot entry either.
ROCKNIX's build is self-compiled via grub-mkimage against upstream GRUB
2.14-rc1 (projects/ROCKNIX/packages/tools/grub in their distribution repo)
with a fixed module list plus a custom framebuffer-rotation patch - live-
tested on real Mini V2 hardware and confirmed working (correct device
auto-selected via saved_entry, readable menu, correct panel orientation)
when paired with armada's own grub.cfg (see finalize-armada-image.sh) rather
than ROCKNIX's own LibreELEC-oriented one, which assumes a completely
different (non-ostree/BLS) root filesystem and boot flow.

Not rebuilt from source ourselves: no isolated/standalone release of this
binary exists upstream (only embedded in their full multi-GB device image/
update-tar releases), and it's a small (~1.1MB combined), static, already-
proven artifact - rebuilding GRUB from source with a matching patch set
would add real build-system complexity for no behavioral difference.

To refresh: download a newer ROCKNIX-SM8250.aarch64-<date>.tar release
asset, extract the same two paths, and replace these files. Re-verify boot,
menu readability, and orientation on real hardware before shipping - this
is bootloader-level, a bad swap can leave a device unable to boot.
